       answer:2, explanation:'The Crust is the thin solid outer shell of Earth where we live.'}
    ]
  },

  matter:{
    title:'States of Matter', readTime:'7 min',
    chunks:[
      {type:'intro', heading:'🧊 What is Matter?',
       text:`Everything around you is made of <span class="key-word" data-def="Anything that has mass and takes up space">matter</span>. Your chair, water, air — it's all matter. Matter exists in three main <span class="key-word" data-def="The different forms matter can take depending on temperature and pressure">states</span>: Solid, Liquid, and Gas.`,
       visual:{icon:'🧊💧☁️', caption:'Ice (solid), Water (liquid), Steam (gas) — all the same substance!'}},
      {type:'key', heading:'🧱 Solid, Liquid, Gas',
       text:`A <span class="key-word" data-def="Matter with fixed shape and volume — particles packed tightly">solid</span> has a fixed shape (like a rock). A <span class="key-word" data-def="Matter with fixed volume but no fixed shape — takes the shape of its container">liquid</span> takes the shape of its container (like juice). A <span class="key-word" data-def="Matter with no fixed shape or volume — particles spread out freely">gas</span> fills all available space (like air).`,
       note:'🔥 Matter changes state when heated or cooled!'},
      {type:'visual', heading:'🌡️ Changing States',
       text:`Heating makes matter change: Ice (solid) → Water (liquid) → Steam (gas). Cooling reverses it: Steam → Water → Ice.`,
       visual:{icon:'🧊→💧→💨', caption:'Heat causes melting (solid→liquid) and evaporation (liquid→gas)'}},
      {type:'text', heading:'⚗️ Examples Around You',
       text:`<span class="key-word" data-def="When a solid turns into a liquid by heating">Melting</span>: chocolate in your hands. <span class="key-word" data-def="When a liquid turns into a gas">Evaporation</span>: puddles disappearing after rain. <span class="key-word" data-def="When a gas cools and turns into a liquid — water droplets on a cold glass">Condensation</span>: water forming on a cold glass.`}
    ],
    flashcards:[
      {front:'Name the 3 states of matter', back:'Solid (fixed shape), Liquid (fixed volume), Gas (no fixed shape or volume).'},
      {front:'What happens when a solid is heated?', back:'It melts and becomes a liquid.'},
      {front:'What is evaporation?', back:'When a liquid turns into a gas by heating — like puddles drying up.'},
      {front:'What is condensation?', back:'When a gas cools and turns into a liquid — like water drops on a cold glass.'},
      {front:'What state does water exist in naturally?', back:'All 3! Ice (solid), Water (liquid), Clouds/Steam (gas).'}
    ],
    quiz:[
      {q:'Which state of matter has a fixed shape?',
       options:['Gas','Liquid','Solid','Plasma'],
       answer:2, explanation:'Solids have particles tightly packed together, giving them a fixed shape.'},
      {q:'What is it called when ice turns into water?',
       options:['Evaporation','Condensation','Melting','Freezing'],
       answer:2, explanation:'Melting is when a solid (ice) absorbs heat and becomes a liquid (water).'},
      {q:'What state does water turn into when it reaches 100°C?',
       options:['Solid','A bigger liquid','Gas (steam)','It disappears'],
       answer:2, explanation:'At 100°C, water evaporates and becomes steam — a gas.'},
      {q:'What is condensation?',
       options:['Gas turning to solid','Liquid turning to gas','Gas cooling into liquid','Solid melting to liquid'],
       answer:2, explanation:'Condensation is when a gas (water vapour) cools and turns into a liquid (water drops).'}
    ]
  },

