  medieval:{
    title:'The Middle Ages', readTime:'8 min',
    chunks:[
      {type:'intro', heading:'🏰 What Were the Middle Ages?',
       text:`The Middle Ages (also called the <span class="key-word" data-def="The historical period from about 500 AD to 1500 AD in Europe">Medieval Period</span>) lasted from about 500 AD to 1500 AD. After the fall of the Roman Empire, Europe changed dramatically. Life revolved around castles, churches, and farming.`,
       visual:{icon:'🏰⚔️⛪', caption:'Castles, knights and cathedrals defined the Middle Ages'}},
      {type:'key', heading:'🤴 Feudal System',
       text:`Society was organized in a <span class="key-word" data-def="A system where kings gave land to lords, who gave it to knights, who protected peasants in return">feudal system</span>. At the top sat the <span class="key-word" data-def="The supreme ruler who owned all land in the kingdom">King</span>. Below were <span class="key-word" data-def="Nobles who received land from the king in return for military service">Lords</span>, then <span class="key-word" data-def="Warriors on horseback who served a lord — promised to protect the weak">Knights</span>, and at the bottom, <span class="key-word" data-def="Farmers who worked the land in return for protection">Peasants</span>.`,
       note:'🧅 Peasants gave much of their food and income to lords as payment (tax).'},
      {type:'visual', heading:'⚔️ The Crusades',
       text:`The <span class="key-word" data-def="A series of religious wars from 1095–1291 where European Christians fought to control Jerusalem">Crusades</span> were a series of religious wars. European kings and knights traveled to the Holy Land (modern Israel/Palestine) to capture Jerusalem.`,
       visual:{icon:'✝️🗺️⚔️🌙', caption:'Crusaders journeyed thousands of miles to fight for holy lands'}},
      {type:'text', heading:'🎭 Life in the Middle Ages',
       text:`Most people were <span class="key-word" data-def="Farmers who lived and worked on a lord's land in exchange for protection">serfs</span> or peasants. The <span class="key-word" data-def="The powerful Christian religious organisation centred in Rome">Catholic Church</span> was very powerful. The <span class="key-word" data-def="A deadly disease (bubonic plague) that killed about 1/3 of Europe's population in the 1300s">Black Death</span> (1347-1351) killed roughly one-third of Europe's people.`}
    ],
    flashcards:[
      {front:'What time period were the Middle Ages?', back:'Roughly 500 AD to 1500 AD — about 1,000 years of history.'},
      {front:'What was the feudal system?', back:'A social structure: King → Lords → Knights → Peasants. Land given in exchange for loyalty and service.'},
      {front:'Who were knights?', back:'Warriors on horseback who served lords, promised to protect people and follow a code of honor.'},
      {front:'What were the Crusades?', back:'Religious wars (1095–1291) where European Christians fought to control Jerusalem.'},
      {front:'What was the Black Death?', back:'A deadly plague (1347–1351) that killed about one-third of Europe\'s population.'}
    ],
    quiz:[
      {q:'When did the Middle Ages take place?',
       options:['100 BC to 100 AD','500 AD to 1500 AD','1600 to 1900','2000 BC to 0 AD'],
       answer:1, explanation:'The Middle Ages ran from roughly 500 AD (fall of Rome) to 1500 AD (start of Renaissance).'},
      {q:'In the feudal system, who was at the very top?',
       options:['Knights','Peasants','Lords','The King'],
       answer:3, explanation:'The King was at the top of the feudal pyramid — he owned all the land in the kingdom.'},
      {q:'What were the Crusades?',
       options:['Agricultural techniques','Military campaigns to control Jerusalem','A type of castle','A peasant revolution'],
       answer:1, explanation:'The Crusades were religious wars (1095-1291) to control the Holy Land (Jerusalem).'},
      {q:'What was the Black Death?',
       options:['A type of armour','A medieval tax','A devastating plague killing ~1/3 of Europe','A famous battle'],
       answer:2, explanation:'The Black Death (bubonic plague, 1347-1351) killed about one-third of Europe\'s entire population.'}
    ]
  },

  modern:{
    title:'Modern World History', readTime:'8 min',
    chunks:[
      {type:'intro', heading:'🌐 What is Modern History?',
       text:`<span class="key-word" data-def="The period of history from roughly 1500 to the present day">Modern history</span> begins around 1500 AD. It includes the <span class="key-word" data-def="A great rebirth of art, science and learning in Europe from the 14th to 17th centuries">Renaissance</span>, the <span class="key-word" data-def="A period from the 18th century when machines replaced hand labor, transforming industry">Industrial Revolution</span>, two World Wars, and the digital age.`,
       visual:{icon:'🏭✈️🌐💻', caption:'From steam engines to the internet — 500 years of change'}},
      {type:'key', heading:'⚙️ The Industrial Revolution',
       text:`The <span class="key-word" data-def="Period (1760s–1840s) when machines powered by coal and steam replaced hand tools in factories">Industrial Revolution</span> began in Britain around the 1760s. Inventions like the <span class="key-word" data-def="An engine powered by steam, used in factories and locomotives">steam engine</span> transformed farming, travel, and factory work. Cities grew rapidly.`,
       note:'🏭 Before factories, most goods were made by hand at home.'},
      {type:'visual', heading:'🌍 The World Wars',
       text:`<span class="key-word" data-def="The First World War (1914–1918) — fought mainly in Europe, killing over 17 million people">World War I</span> (1914–1918) and <span class="key-word" data-def="The Second World War (1939–1945) — the deadliest conflict in human history, killing over 70 million">World War II</span> (1939–1945) were the deadliest conflicts in human history. WWII ended with the atomic bombing of Japan and the Holocaust.`,
       visual:{icon:'🌍⚔️🕊️', caption:'Two World Wars reshaped the political map of the entire Earth'}},
      {type:'text', heading:'💻 The Digital Age',
