      {type:'key', heading:'🔀 Logic and Conditions',
       text:`Computers make decisions using <span class="key-word" data-def="Logical statements that check if something is true or false — if-then-else">if-then-else</span> statements. Example: IF the light is red → STOP. ELSE → GO. This is <span class="key-word" data-def="A type of thinking that uses clear rules and reasoning to solve problems">logical thinking</span>.`,
       note:'🤔 Programmers call this "conditional logic" — it\'s the foundation of all computer programs!'},
      {type:'visual', heading:'🔄 Loops',
       text:`A <span class="key-word" data-def="A programming instruction that repeats a set of steps multiple times">loop</span> repeats instructions until a condition is met. Like "brush each tooth" — you repeat for every tooth. <span class="key-word" data-def="A loop that repeats while a condition remains true">While loops</span> and <span class="key-word" data-def="A loop that repeats a fixed number of times">for loops</span> are common in code.`,
       visual:{icon:'🔄🔄🔄', caption:'Loops repeat steps automatically — no need to write them out again and again'}},
      {type:'text', heading:'🧩 Decomposition',
       text:`<span class="key-word" data-def="Breaking a big problem down into smaller, manageable steps">Decomposition</span> is the art of breaking big problems into smaller pieces. Great programmers think: "How can I break this into smaller steps?" This makes hard problems solvable.`}
    ],
    flashcards:[
