  'critical-thinking':{
    title:'Critical Thinking', readTime:'7 min',
    chunks:[
      {type:'intro', heading:'🧠 What is Critical Thinking?',
       text:`<span class="key-word" data-def="The ability to analyse information objectively and make reasoned judgements rather than accepting things blindly">Critical thinking</span> is thinking clearly and carefully before believing or deciding something. It means asking "how do I know this?" and "what's the evidence?"`,
       visual:{icon:'🧠❓🔍⚖️', caption:'Critical thinkers question, analyse and reason before concluding'}},
      {type:'key', heading:'🔍 The 5 Critical Thinking Steps',
       text:`1. <span class="key-word" data-def="Clearly define what question or problem you are trying to solve">Identify the question</span>. 2. <span class="key-word" data-def="Find reliable facts and data from credible sources">Gather evidence</span>. 3. <span class="key-word" data-def="Consider whether the evidence is reliable and the reasoning is valid">Evaluate it</span>. 4. <span class="key-word" data-def="Think about all sides of the issue fairly">Consider other viewpoints</span>. 5. <span class="key-word" data-def="Form a conclusion based on the evidence you've analysed">Draw a conclusion</span>.`,
       note:'❗ Misinformation spreads fast online — critical thinking helps you spot fake news!'},
      {type:'visual', heading:'⚖️ Bias and Fallacies',
       text:`A <span class="key-word" data-def="A tendency to favour certain information because of personal preferences, not evidence">bias</span> is a mental shortcut that skews our thinking. A <span class="key-word" data-def="An error in reasoning that makes an argument logically invalid">logical fallacy</span> is a faulty argument. Example: "Everyone believes X" is not evidence X is true.`,
